{
  "doc_id": "13700",
  "text": "The Cip/Kip families of cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitors (CKI) are the main effectors linking developmental programs and cell cycle progression [CITATION_1] . Drosophila dacapo (dap) encodes an inhibitor of cyclin E/cdk2 complexes with similarity to the vertebrate Cip/Kip inhibitors [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and thereby inhibits entry into the S-phase. In accordance with this role, mammalian family members are upregulated during checkpoint activation and are expressed in terminally differentiated tissues. Dacapo contains a conserved aminoterminal domain that binds to and inhibits all kinases involved in G1/S transition. This inhibition is achieved by a conformational change in the cyclin/Cdk complex [CITATION_5] .",
